<h2>Basic Chemistry of Life</h2>
<h2><span style="font-weight:400;">Essential Elements of Life</span></h2>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">About 25 elements are essential for life</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Four elements make up 96% of living matter</span></li>
</ul>
<span style="font-weight:400;">CHONPS</span>
<ul>
	<li><strong>Carbon</strong></li>
	<li><strong>Hydrogen</strong></li>
	<li><strong>Oxygen</strong></li>
	<li>
<p style="display:inline !important;"><strong>Nitrogen</strong></p>
</li>
	<li>
<p style="display:inline !important;"><strong>Phosphorous</strong></p>
</li>
	<li>
<p style="display:inline !important;"><strong>Sulfur</strong></p>
</li>
</ul>
(Calcium, Potassium)
<h1><span style="font-weight:400;">(Pt. 1) Bonding Properties</span></h1>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Electrons determine the chemical behavior of atoms</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">The behavior of the atoms depends on the number of valence electrons in an atom</span></li>
</ul>
<span style="font-weight:400;"> <em>ex.¬†</em>Noble gas</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Valence shell is full</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Stable and unreactive</span></li>
</ul>
<span style="font-weight:400;"> <em>ex.¬†</em>Atom with 2 valence electrons</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Very reactive</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Wants to lose 2 electrons</span></li>
</ul>
<span style="font-weight:400;"> <em>ex.¬†</em>Atom with 6 valence electrons</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Very reactive</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Wants to gain 2 electrons</span></li>
</ul>
<h3><span style="font-weight:400;">Chemical Reactivity</span></h3>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Atoms tend to:</span></li>
</ul>
<ol>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Complete a partially filled valence shell OR</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Empty a partially filled valence shell</span></li>
</ol>
<span style="font-weight:400;">This tendency drives chemical reactions and creates bonds: ionic bonds - one atom gives an electron to the other, covalent bonds - two atoms share an electron</span>
<h2><span style="font-weight:400;">Bonds in Biology</span></h2>
<h3><span style="font-weight:400;">Weak Bonds</span></h3>
<b>Intermolecular </b><span style="font-weight:400;">(between molecules)</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Hydrogen bonds</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Attraction between positively and negatively charged atoms</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Hydrophobic & hydrophilic interactions</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Interactions with H</span><span style="font-weight:400;">2</span><span style="font-weight:400;">O</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">vanderWaals forces </span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">LDF</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Dipole-dipole</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Ionic</span></li>
</ul>
<span style="font-weight:400;">Intermolecular bonds in chemistry must be weak in order for molecules to move within the cell. If all of the bonds were permanent, the cell couldn‚Äôt function/replicate.</span>
<h3><span style="font-weight:400;">Strong Bonds</span></h3>
<b>Intramolecular</b><span style="font-weight:400;"> (within molecules)</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Covalent bonds</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">They have full valence shells and are stable</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<h2><span style="font-weight:400;">Covalent Bonds</span></h2>
<b>Why are covalent bonds so strong?</b>
<ul>
	<li><span style="font-weight:400;">Two atoms </span><span style="font-weight:400;">share</span><span style="font-weight:400;"> a pair of electrons</span>
<ul>
	<li><span style="font-weight:400;">Both atoms are holding onto those electrons</span></li>
	<li><i><span style="font-weight:400;">The molecule that is formed is very stable</span></i></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<em>ex.¬†</em>H2 (hydrogen gas)
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Equal share of electrons</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Pure covalent bond</span></li>
</ul>
<h3><span style="font-weight:400;">Multiple Covalent Bonds</span></h3>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Atoms can share more than one pair of electrons</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Double bonds mean that a molecule is sharing two pairs of electrons</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Triple bonds mean that a molecule is sharing three pairs of electrons</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<h3><span style="font-weight:400;">Polar Covalent Bonds</span></h3>
<b>Polar covalent bonds: </b><span style="font-weight:400;">Pair of covalent bonds shared unequally by 2 atoms, creating a dipole</span>

<span style="font-weight:400;"><em>ex.¬†</em>Water (H</span><span style="font-weight:400;">2</span><span style="font-weight:400;">O)</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Oxygen has a stronger attraction for the electrons than hydrogen</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Oxygen has higher </span><span style="font-weight:400;">electronegativity</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Water is a polar molecule</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">It has negative and positive poles</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">This creates the very unique properties of water</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<h2><span style="font-weight:400;">Hydrogen Bonding</span></h2>
Polar water creates molecular attractions
<ul>
	<li>The attraction between the ùõø+ Hydrogen in one H2O molecule and the ùõø- Oxygen in another H2O molecule</li>
	<li>This can also occur whenever a -OH exists in a larger molecule</li>
</ul>
Hydrogen bonds are weak compared to covalent bonds
<ul>
	<li>This is good because hydrogen molecules need to be sent to different parts of the cell</li>
	<li><span style="font-weight:400;">(Pt. 2) Properties of Water</span></li>
</ul>
<b>All life occurs in water, both inside and outside of the cell</b>
<h2><span style="font-weight:400;">Chemistry of Water</span></h2>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">H</span><span style="font-weight:400;">2</span><span style="font-weight:400;">O molecules form hydrogen bonds with each other</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">+H is attracted to -O</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">This creates a </span><span style="font-weight:400;">sticky molecule</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Water molecules stick to each other; it takes energy (heat) to separate them </span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">The heat can break the bonds between molecules, but not within molecules</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<h2><span style="font-weight:400;">Special Properties of Water</span></h2>
<ol>
	<li>Cohesion & Adhesion
<ul>
	<li><span style="font-weight:400;">Surface tension, capillary action</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
	<li>Good Solvent (not universal)
<ul>
	<li><span style="font-weight:400;">Many molecules dissolve in H</span><span style="font-weight:400;">2</span><span style="font-weight:400;">O</span></li>
	<li><span style="font-weight:400;">Hydrophobic vs. Hydrophilic</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
	<li>Lower density as a solid
<ul>
	<li><span style="font-weight:400;">Ice floats</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
	<li>High specific heat
<ul>
	<li><span style="font-weight:400;">Water stores heat</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
	<li>High heat of vapourization
<ul>
	<li><span style="font-weight:400;">Heats & cools slowly</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ol>
<h3><span style="font-weight:400;">Cohesion and Adhesion</span></h3>
<b>Cohesion</b>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Hydrogen bonding between H</span><span style="font-weight:400;">2</span><span style="font-weight:400;">O</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Water is ‚Äústicky‚Äù</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">It has surface tension</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">ex. drinking straw (the water sticks to the outside of the straw to move up it)</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<b>Adhesion</b>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Hydrogen bonding between H</span><span style="font-weight:400;">2</span><span style="font-weight:400;">O and other substance</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Capillary action</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Meniscus</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Water climbs up paper towel or cloth</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<ol>
	<li><span style="font-weight:400;"> How water gets to the top of a tree</span></li>
</ol>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Water travels up the tree through the xylem and leaves through the tomato</span></li>
</ul>
<h3><span style="font-weight:400;">Good Solvent</span></h3>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">The </span><span style="font-weight:400;">polarity</span><span style="font-weight:400;"> of H</span><span style="font-weight:400;">2</span><span style="font-weight:400;">O makes it a </span><span style="font-weight:400;">good solvent</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Polar water molecules surround positive and negative ions, pulling them apart</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">The positive hydrogen is attracted to the negative ions, and the negative oxygen is attracted to the positive ions</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Solvents dissolve solutes, creating solutions</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<h4><span style="font-weight:400;">Dissolves in Water</span></h4>
<b>Hydrophilic</b>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Substances have attraction to H</span><span style="font-weight:400;">2</span><span style="font-weight:400;">O</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Polar molecule</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;">Does Not Dissolve in Water</li>
</ul>
<b>Hydrophobic</b>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Substances that don‚Äôt have an attraction to H</span><span style="font-weight:400;">2</span><span style="font-weight:400;">O</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Non-polar molecule</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Hydrocarbons - do not have an OH molecule that makes them polar</span></li>
</ul>
<h3><span style="font-weight:400;">Lower Density as a Solid</span></h3>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Most substances are more dense when they are solid. However, water is different.</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Ice floats</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Hydrogen bonds form a crystal, allowing them to float</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">It is important that lakes don‚Äôt freeze solid</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Surface ice insulates water below</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Allows life to survive in the winter</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">If ice sank:</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Ponds, lakes, etc. would freeze over</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">In summer, only a few inches would thaw</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">The melting of ice helps with seasonal turnover in lakes</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Sinking cold water cycles H</span><span style="font-weight:400;">2</span><span style="font-weight:400;">O through the lake</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<h3><span style="font-weight:400;">High Specific Heat</span></h3>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">H</span><span style="font-weight:400;">2</span><span style="font-weight:400;">O resists changes in temperature</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">It has a high specific heat, meaning it takes a lot to heat it up, and a lot to cool it down</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">H</span><span style="font-weight:400;">2</span><span style="font-weight:400;">O moderated temperatures on Earth</span></li>
</ul>
<h3><span style="font-weight:400;">High Heat of Vapourization</span></h3>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Water absorbs a lot of heat before it evaporates</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">This helps with </span><span style="font-weight:400;">evaporative cooling</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Our sweat absorbs as much of our body heat as it can before evaporating, cooling us down</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<h2><span style="font-weight:400;">Ionization of Water & pH</span></h2>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Water ionizes</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">H+ splits off from H</span><span style="font-weight:400;">2</span><span style="font-weight:400;">O, leaving OH-</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">If [H+] = [-OH], the water is neutral</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">The hydrogen and hydroxide concentrations are equal</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">If [H+] > [-OH], the water is acidic</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">There is more hydrogen than hydroxide</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">If [H+] < [-OH], the water is basic</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">There is more hydroxide than hydrogen</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">pH scale refers to how acidic or basic a solution is</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">1=acidic</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">7=neutral</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">14=basic</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">pH is measured on a log scale</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<h2><span style="font-weight:400;">Buffers & Cell Regulation</span></h2>
<ul>
	<li style="list-style-type:none;">
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">The pH of cells must be kept neutral (7)</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">pH affects the shape of molecules</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">The shapes of the molecules affects their function</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Therefore, </span><b>the pH of a cell affects its function</b></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<ul>
	<li><b>pH is controlled by a buffer</b></li>
	<li style="list-style-type:none;">
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">This buffer is a </span><b>reservoir of H+</b>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">It donates H+ when the [H+] falls</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">It absorbs H+ when the [H+] rises</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
